Breville Group Ltd: Looking through the noise (20 August 2025)  Baby Bunting: Growth Reborn (15 August 2025)  ARB Corporation: Driving ahead (19 August 2025)  Peter Warren Automotive Holdings Ltd: Self help + cycle. Move OW (21 August 2025)
Base- case valuation, rounded average of P/E and DCF - A \(\) 44.00\$

P/E relative: base case ascribed 29x FY27e - which factors in ARB's high- quality global franchise, our view on growth opportunities offshore in particular and the resilience of ARB's domestic franchise and pricing power (basically in line with the 28x five- year average).
DCF: WACC \(9.2\%\) , terminal growth \(3.5\%\)
Better than expected growth in Aus cycling strong new vehicle sales. Strong export segment growth continues - particularly driven by US execution Strong OEM collaboration volumes + economics.
Weaker Aus growth and more uncertainty on a core part of the business Strong rebound in US growth short- lived OEM collaborations economics and take- up of ARB package is worse than expected.
Base case, equal- weighted blend of P/E, EV/EBITDA, & DCF.
P/E: 17x FY27e EPS, slightly below historical average reflecting; historical range, improved recent performance and levers to drive improvement.
EV/EBITDA: 8x FY27e EBITDA, same as P/E.
DCF: WACC \(10.5\%\) , terminal growth \(3\%\)
Improving comp growth, and Traction with new store format Accelerated store roll- out Moderating headwinds from NZ and marketplace start up
Diminished resilience of baby goods category AUD softness Increased competition Falling short of store and margin targets Macro slowdown and/or erosion of consumer confidence
Approximate midpoint of our fundamental value range.
P/E: 35x FY27E, a c.10% premium to BRG's 5- year average of 31x (but below the upper bound
DCF: WACC 9.2%, terminal growth rate 3.0%
- New country launches- New product launches- Market share gains- Price increases- Fixed-cost leverage resulting in EBIT margin expansion- Further M&A
- Economic slowdown- Higher competition from global peers- Supply-chain disruptions- Cost inflation- Stronger USD- US tariffs
Base case valuation, average of P/E and DCF - A\$2.30

P/E relative: base 13x FY27e - Our multiple is at the upper bound of PWR's listed history, reflecting GM stability (a key drag last 2yrs), evident self help, and lesser cyclical headwinds (potentially tailwinds) going forward.
DCF: WACC 10.3%, terminal growth 2%.
- Continued stabilisation/recovery in vehicle sales- Increasing F&I penetration rates- Increasing used car sales (and used/new ratio)- Greater back-end contributions- Further M&A
- Limited changes to F&I penetration- Saturation on used/new ratios- Deteriorating macro conditions- Mis-execution on network expansion (organically or inorganically)

Overweight (O). The stock's total return is expected to exceed the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.

Equal-weight (E). The stock's total return is expected to be in line with the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.

Not-Rated (NR). Currently the analyst does not have adequate conviction about the stock's total return relative to the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.

Underweight (U). The stock's total return is expected to be below the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.
